Man: Infinity (symbol: ‚àû) is an abstract concept describing something without any bound and is relevant in a number of fields, predominantly mathematics and physics. In mathematics, "infinity" is often treated as if it were a number (i.e., it counts or measures things: "an infinite number of terms") but it is not the same sort of number as natural or real numbers.

Georg Cantor formalized many ideas related to infinity and infinite sets during the late 19th and early 20th centuries. In the theory he developed, there are infinite sets of different sizes (called cardinalities).[1] For example, the set of integers is countably infinite, while the infinite set of real numbers is uncountable.

I really hope Bollywood doesn't attempt to make movies within its current framework. I minored 
in History as an Undergrad, where my broader interest was on the 
influence of Indian Sub-Continent on the development of emergence of 
liberal values in the West. In particular, I was extremely interested in
 Emperor Ashok,
 I find the man fascinating. A man brought up to expand and condolidate 
power through any means necessary, questions the futility of violence in
 achieving his ends, but also goes onto implement policies that seek to 
redress the death and destruction his campaigns have brought on his 
people by espousing the ideas of human rights and liberty and ensuring 
its survival by carving them into words on stone. 

It was this fascination that led me to write a paper on his ideas of human rights and liberty and whether this had any influence on British who ruled India and were withdrawing from the contininent when the United Nation adopted the Declaration on Human Rights in 1948. ( my conclusions are for a different time and forum). But that said,  I mentioned this to  an Indian co-worker  in my IT department at my company  and the well-intentioned co-worker brought a DVD of a movie titled, "Ashoka".  She said it was a classic and must see. 

OMG!! I wish I hadn't seen it. It was the worst movie ever made on one of the greatest rulers to have ever lived. The movie had lots of singing and dancing and over the top acting. Even soap operas are less dramatic than this terrible movie. Of course, I  didn't tell my co-worker this and stated I thought it was very entertaining, which it was, if it could be passed off as a parody of Ashok's life. I refrained from telling her, I have actually read Kautilya's Arthashastra and believed him to a genius in the art of ruling, out of fear I would be given an another DVD with Kautilya breaking into dance and song in the middle of nowhere with some random girl. 

I believe the sub-continent history is littered with increadible scientists, innovators, rulers, leaders,  philosophers, artists, writers, adventurers , and entrepreneurs. It is sad the only thing that most of the world knows about India is yoga, IT Services and Slum Dog Millionaire.

So glad this story is finally be told on the big screen.  Ramanujan was a true genius and used that genius to make amazing discoveries for which there are still conferences on trying to figure out the almost magical insight of this man.  He was self-educated by reading primarily a single book...which was a uniquely condensed yet comprehensive text of mathematical proofs Carr's A Synopsis of Elementary Results in Pure and Applied Mathematics.  The text is available now on amazon, but was also able to be downloaded for free from the Internet Archive and google books a few years ago.   Its a fascinating read which because it doesn't have the fluff that most modern publishers use for dubious reasons of adding unecessary heft for profit, would not bore a budding genius and allow him to reach a new potential quickly.  His story really speaks to the fact that there are great people from humble backgrounds who can achieve miraculous things if they have the right education and support.  I wonder how many Ramanjan's there are out there thoughout the world who have never had the opportunity to reach their potential.

I remember reading about him in the Encyclopaedia Brittanica... A professor 
at Oxford received a letter, read a little of it, and then threw it in his waste basket, for he 
was used to getting letters from "crackpots" claiming to have solved this, or that... But he had a feeling.. so he took the letter out of the waste basket... and soon realized that it 
was written by a kid in a village in India, who had stumbled upon a math textbook, taught 
himself from it, and then.. invented the rest... but what he invented was stuff already discovered by great western minds such as Gauss and Euler and others.. not knowing 
of what they had done... so he invited him to Oxford to fill in the blanks... In time, he hated his eccentricities, namely his Hindu fatalism - if he got sick, refused to see a doctor, calling it karma, or whatever... Once he was in a cab with a professor who looked
 at a license plate and said casuaaly, What a boring number.  And Ramanujan replied 
something like, Actually it is an interesting number, being prime... It was like four digits.
... I think he might have made some contribution in astrophysics.. no, not Chandreshkar, 
but Ramanujan... I don't know... my memory comes and goes.

When he joined college he could only concentrate on maths and he failed in other subjects so he ran away! He worked as a clerk! After finding his amazing knowledge over mathematics, Professor from Trinity college, Cambridge called him to England! And the rest is history!

Everyone's talking about how Tom Hanks is barely in this but all I can think is how repulsively ugly the cinematography for this is. I know this is supposed to be an uplifting movie but does the cinematographer really think blowing out every window and lathering a sappy glow over every surface is the best way to do that? Is this a Disney live action remake or is this a period piece? The main character looks like he has eight layers of CGI effects added to his face when if we were supposed to identify with him as a believable and relatable character he should look like every other kid his age, not an actor from Twilight. And most alarmingly those brief scenes of soldiers look positively cartoonish. It comes as no surprise that the DP listed, Andrew Dunn, normally does romantic comedies but he could learn a few things from the grounded and realistic cinematography of other war-era films with Tom Hanks in them, as it suits this type of work much much better if its creators want it to be taken seriously.
